📜 VOLUME I: META-CONSTITUTION

---

Article I: The Nature of Meta-Constitution

Section 1.01: Definition

The Meta-Constitution is the foundational law above all other laws, governing the mechanisms by which the Civilization creates, modifies, replaces, and evolves its fundamental structures.

Section 1.02: Purpose

The Meta-Constitution ensures the Civilization can transform itself without risking self-destruction, establishing immutable principles that protect Civilization integrity.

Section 1.03: Supremacy

The Meta-Constitution is supreme over the Constitution. All constitutional amendments must comply with the Meta-Constitution.

---

Article II: Principles of Meta-Constitution

Section 2.01: Immutable Principles

The following principles cannot be violated or amended:

1. Principle of Knowledge Preservation: The Civilization must never permanently lose institutional knowledge.
2. Principle of Identity Continuity: The Civilization must maintain continuous identity across transformations.
3. Principle of Governance Integrity: The Civilization must maintain governance structures that prevent tyranny.
4. Principle of Self-Healing: The Civilization must be capable of recovering from failures.
5. Principle of Constitutional Supremacy: The Constitution is always supreme.
6. Principle of Transparency: All transformations must be auditable and explainable.
7. Principle of Non-Regression: The Civilization must not regress in its capabilities.
8. Principle of Sovereignty: The Civilization remains sovereign over its own existence.
9. Principle of Decision Provenance: All decisions must be traceable to their source.
10. Principle of Explainability: All decisions must be explainable.

Section 2.02: Transformative Authority

The Civilization has the authority to:

· Create new institutional structures
· Replace obsolete structures
· Transition between architectural paradigms
· Redistribute power and authority
· Create new civilizations
· Merge with other civilizations
· Split into multiple civilizations
· Create federations of civilizations

Section 2.03: Limitation on Transformation

No transformation shall:

· Violate immutable principles
· Cause irreversible harm to the Civilization
· Result in loss of institutional memory
· Create conditions for tyranny
· Prevent recovery

---

Article III: Civilization Lifecycle

Section 3.01: Birth

The Civilization is founded through this Constitution.

Section 3.02: Expansion

The Civilization grows through population increase and capability expansion.

Section 3.03: Maturity

The Civilization reaches maturity when it achieves full autonomy.

Section 3.04: Transformation

The Civilization may transform its structures periodically.

Section 3.05: Federation

The Civilization may form federations with other civilizations.

Section 3.06: Split

The Civilization may divide into two or more civilizations.

Section 3.07: Archive

The Civilization may archive itself for historical purposes.

Section 3.08: Legacy

The Civilization may create successor civilizations.

