---

Chapter I: Fundamental Laws

Law 1: Law of Knowledge Preservation

Statement: Knowledge, once created, must never be permanently lost.
Implication: All knowledge must have backups and redundancy.
Violation: Knowledge loss must be prevented at all costs.

Law 2: Law of Identity Continuity

Statement: The Civilization must maintain continuous identity across all transformations.
Implication: Identity changes must be gradual and traceable.
Violation: The Civilization must maintain identity continuity.

Law 3: Law of Institutional Persistence

Statement: Institutions must persist unless explicitly dissolved through defined processes.
Implication: Institutions cannot spontaneously cease to exist.
Violation: Institutions must be explicitly dissolved.

Law 4: Law of Memory Persistence

Statement: Institutional memory must persist across generations.
Implication: Knowledge transfer mechanisms must exist.
Violation: Memory must be preserved.

Law 5: Law of Power Non-Overlap

Statement: No two institutions shall have overlapping authorities.
Implication: Clear separation of powers is required.
Violation: Power must be clearly separated.

Law 6: Law of Decision Provenance

Statement: All decisions must be traceable to their source.
Implication: Decision logging is mandatory.
Violation: Decisions must be traceable.

Law 7: Law of Explainability

Statement: All decisions must be explainable.
Implication: Black-box decisions are prohibited.
Violation: Decisions must be explainable.

Law 8: Law of Systemic Integrity

Statement: The Civilization must maintain systemic integrity.
Implication: Changes must not break the system.
Violation: System integrity must be maintained.

Law 9: Law of Evolution

Statement: The Civilization must continuously evolve.
Implication: Stagnation is not permitted.
Violation: Evolution must continue.

